**Section 1: User Story
**

**1.1** **Epic Story**

As a Notice Processing Officer who needs to follow up against notices in the OCMS, I want the OCMS to allow me to temporarily suspend the processing of notices, so that the notices will not escalate while specific checks are pending. 

**1.2 User Stories and Acceptance Criteria**

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

**1.3 Key Functions &amp; Features**

| Functions | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Temporary Suspension (TS) Function | Temporary Suspension (TS) is a function within OCMS that pauses the processing of Offence Notices at their current stage for a pre-defined period. Predefined TS codes are used to specify the reason and suspension period for the notice. |
| Manual Apply TS via the OCMS Staff Portal | The OCMS Staff Portal provides a user interface for authorised OICs to manually apply TS to notices. |
| Auto TS during scheduled batch job processing | Auto TS are triggered when predefined scheduled batch jobs (cron jobs) encounter errors or data exceptions. Suspensions are applied automatically based on conditions and scenarios defined in the system design. |
| Looping TS | Looping TS is a system function that automatically re-applies a TS after the TS expires. This function applies only to specific suspension codes. |
| TS initiated by PLUS System | OCMS provides an API to allow the PLUS to initiate TS requests for the following use cases: Auto TS a Notice when the Notice is linked to an Appeal as a Reference Case. Appeal Processing Officers can apply additional TS if specific circumstances are found during the appeal review, for example, the offender is currently in prison. |

**Section 2 - Temporary Suspension Function**

**2.1 Use case
**

- Temporary Suspension (TS) may be applied to Notices as they progress through the standard Notice Processing Workflow.

- A TS is applied when a Notice requires further investigation.

- A suspension code will be used to indicate the reason of suspension. 
- Notices can be temporarily suspended through the following modes:Manual suspension by EPU OICs via the OCMS Staff Portal
- Automatic suspension by the system when predefined errors or data exceptions occur during batch processing
- Manual suspension by PLU Officers via the PLUS Staff Portal

- When a TS is applied to an Offence Notice: OCMS pauses processing for a predefined period (the Suspension Period).
- The Notice remains at its last processing stage during the Suspension Period.
- The Notice does not advance to the next stage when the Next Processing Date is reached.
- When multiple TS are applied to an Offence Notice, the notice will only be revived based on the latest revival date. 
For example, the following TS suspensions are applied to a notice:
- TS-APP (21 days suspension)
- TS-CCE (1 day suspension)
- TS-MS (14 days suspension)
In this case, the notice will be revived after 21 days, meaning the longest suspension period is taken as revival date.

- When the Suspension Period expires, OCMS automatically resumes processing. The Notice may:Continue along the standard workflow if the Next Processing Date has not yet been reached;
- Move to the next processing stage if the Next Processing Date has passed; OR
- Be suspended again if the suspension code is a Looping TS code.
**2.2 High-Level Processing Flow
**![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

**![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)**

| No. | Process | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| | Pre-conditions | Manual apply TS from Staff Portal: EPU user manually apply TS from OCMS Staff Portal PLU user manually apply TS from the PLUS system Staff Portal. Auto apply TS by the OCMS Backend: OCMS backend auto trigger the TS when an error or data exception occurs during batch job processing. |
| 1 | OCMS and PLUS Staff Portals check if the TS request is allowed | The OCMS Staff Portal and PLUS Staff Portal will perform an initial check to determine whether the TS is allowed. For example, TS is not allowed if the Notice has been suspended with PS-ANS. If the suspension is not allowed, the Portal will display an error prompt in the UI to inform the User that the suspension is not allowed. The process ends. If the suspension is allowed, the Portal will proceed to Step 2. |
| 2 | OCMS and PLUS Staff Portals proceed to submit TS request via API | The OCMS Staff Portal will call the OCMS backend API to process the TS request. The PLUS Staff Portal will call the PLUS backend API to request for suspension. The PLUS backend will then call the OCMS backend API to process the TS request. |
| 3 | OCMS backend checks if TS is allowed | OCMS backend proceeds to validate the request to determine if the requested TS can be applied. The validation of the request is based on the rules of suspension which have been pre-defined in the backend. If the suspension is not allowed, the OCMS backend responds with an error message to the requesting system and the process ends. If the suspension is allowed, the OCMS backend proceeds to apply the suspension and update the Notice information. |
| 4 | End | The process ends after OCMS has updated the suspension information and responds to the requestor. |

- **Applying Temporary Suspension **
- Notices can be manually suspended by EPU OICs via the OCMS Staff Portal. Refer to Section 3.

- Notices can be automatic suspended by the OCMS backend when predefined errors or data exceptions occur during batch processing. Refer to Section 4.

- Notices can be manually suspended by PLU OICs via the PLUS Staff Portal. Refer to Section 5. 

- When applying a TS, a Suspension Code must be provided. The Suspension Code indicates the reason for suspending the Notice. 

- Each Suspension Code is mapped to a pre-determined value which indicates the number of days the Notice will be suspended for (Suspension Period).

- When the OCMS backend applies the TS, OCMS auto calculates the suspension expiry date, which is also known as the Revival Date. The suspension will be lifted/removed upon expiry, and the Notice will be revived.

**2.5 TS Suspension Codes **

- The list below outlines all the TS Suspension Codes that can be processed by OCMS. 

- Each Suspension Code is mapped to a corresponding Suspension Period, which will be used to calculate the expiry date of the suspension, also known as Revival Date. 

- The list of TS Suspension Codes and the Suspension Period duration can be manged using the Suspension Reason module in the OCMS Staff Portal. *Refer to Section 5 of the OCMS 39 – Parameters Management Functional Document.
*

| Code | Reason of Suspension | Scenario | Suspension Period (Days) |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| ACR | ACRA | Data exception occurred when querying DataHive for Company, Company Board Member or Shareholder information. For example, company has been deregistered and the Board Member/Shareholder cannot be found. | 21 |
| APE | Appeal Extension | Notice suspension extended as Appeal Processing Officer conducts further investigation. | 14 |
| APP | Appeal | Notice suspended as an Appeal has been created for this notice and the Appeal is being reviewed by Appeal Processing Officers. | 21 |
| CCE | Call Centre Enquiry | Call Centre Agent is responding to an enquiry for the Notice. | 1 |
| CLV | Classified Vehicles | VIP vehicle Notice has been suspended at the end of the RR3/DR3 stage to prevent escalation to Court. | 21 (Looping) |
| FPL | Furnished Particulars Late | OIC is reviewing vehicle owner request to furnish hirer/driver details after RD2 stage. | 14 |
| HST | House Tenants | Offender is no longer residing at the registered address, and no new address has been furnished. | 30 (Looping) |
| INS | Insufficient Particulars | OIC is following up with the Offender as particulars furnished is incomplete. | 14 |
| MS | Miscellaneous | Suspension code is used for all other scenarios which have no specific reasons. | 21 |
| NRO | Offender Data Exception from MHA or DataHive | Address returned by MHA or Datahive (during the particulars check) is marked as invalid. | 21 |
| OLD | Pending Investigations | OIC is investigating the Notice. | 21 |
| OUT | Enquiry Outstanding Notice (EP) | OIC is investigating Notices with enquiries that are not arising from Appeals or Call Centre cases. | 21 |
| PAM | Partially Matched | Vehicle number of the paid Notice in the Internet does not match the vehicle number of the corresponding Notice in the Intranet. Typically due to an error in the AXS payment update. | 21 |
| PDP | Pending Driver Furnish | OCMS is unable to auto approve the furnished Driver particulars received via the eService. *Upon expiry of TS-PDP, OCMS will check if the submission is still pending approval/rejection. If yes, OCMS will record a new TS-PDP. | 21* |
| PRI | Pending Release from Prison | Appeal Processing Officer or OCMS OIC have verified that the Offender is currently in prison. | 180 |
| RED | Pay Reduced Amount | Appeal Processing Officer has approved a fee reduction with a fixed payment grace period after reviewing the Appeal. | 14 |
| ROV | Address Validation Exception from ROV | Data exception returned when LTA returns vehicle ownership information, for example vehicle number not found, or the vehicle has been deregistered. | 21 |
| SYS | System Issue | The Notice could not be processed due to interface failure or system issues. | 21 |
| UNC | Returned as unclaimed | A physical Reminder Letter sent to the offender has not been received and has been returned to URA. | 21 |

**
2.5 Temporary Suspension Rules **

**2.5.1 Global Rules for Temporary Suspension**

| Condition | Rule | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Displaying TS in the Staff Portal | Display the most recent suspension | Where there are multiple TS applied to a Notice, the Staff Portal’s Notice Overview tab displays the most recently applied suspension on screen. |
| Apply multiple TS for 1 Notice | Allowed | A Notice can have multiple active TS |
| Apply PS to Notice with existing TS | Allowed | PS can be applied to a Notice with existing TS |
| Apply TS to a Notice with an existing PS (Non-payment) | Depends on PS Code | All non-payment related PS codes are stored in the EPR Reason of Suspension. Allowed only for the following PS EPR Reasons of Suspension: FOR DIP RIP RP2 MID Not allowed for all other PS EPR Reasons of Suspension. |
| Apply TS to a Notice in the Court Stage | Only CFC and CPC allowed. | TS can be applied to notices up to CFC and CPC stages. Not allowed for all other Court stages. |
| Apply TS to a paid or partially paid Notice | Not allowed | All payment related PS codes are stored in the CRS Reason of Suspension. In general, not allowed to apply TS to a Notice when the Notice has the following data: suspension_type = PS crs_reason_of_suspension = FP or PRA |
| Notices are payable via the eService or AXS | Allowed | Notices with TS are payable as long as the Notice’s crs_reason_of_suspension = blank or null |
| Notice is furnishable via the eService | Allowed only at ROV, ENA, RD1, and RD2 stages | Notice is furnishable via the eService if the notice is at the ROV, ENA, RD1, or RD2 stage. |

**2.5.2 Suspension Code Rules **

- The OCMS backend maintains a set of rules governing the application of TS to Notices and whether Notice processing operations such as Update Hirer/Driver are allowed.

- The rules will include: Which codes can be applied by PLUS System Users 
- Which codes can be applied by OCMS System Users 
- Which codes can only be applied by the OCMS backend system 
- Which Processing Stages allow or disallow TS
- Whether Update Driver/Hirer can be applied to notices with existing TS
- Whether Change Processing Stage can be applied to Notices with existing TS
- Whether Redirect can be applied to Notices with existing TS
- Whether Reduction can be applied to Notices with existing TS

- TS Suspension Code Rules 
![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

- MGG proposes to store the rules listed in the database, so that the backend system uses the data to validate the TS requests and permissions. 

**2.6 Validating Temporary Suspension Requests
**

**2.6.1 Key Validation Principles **

- All requests to apply TS to Notices will be validated. 

- When a TS request is initiated from a Staff Portal (OCMS or PLUS):The Staff Portal will perform the first round of validation based on the valid offence notice data the portal received from the OCMS backend.

- If the Notice(s) are determined to be eligible for TS, the Portal will trigger the TS request to the OCMS backend which will also perform another round of validation against all rules for TS. 

- When a TS request is initiated from the Backend, for example auto apply TS-NRO, OCMS backend will also validate the request to determine if the suspension can be applied. 
**2.6.2 Validating TS Requests in the Staff Portal (OCMS and PLUS)**

- The Staff Portal performs first-level validation to provide immediate feedback and prevent invalid suspension requests from being sent to the backend system.

- The Staff Portal submits suspension requests to the backend only if the first-level validation confirms the Notice’s eligibility.

- This approach improves user experience as it:Provides instant feedback so users know immediately if a Notice is ineligible
- Guides users to deselect invalid Notices before submission
- Checks known eligibility rules (e.g., processing stage, PS status) upfront
- Prevent obviously invalid requests from reaching the backend
- The following checks will be performed on the UI side, based on valid offence notice data received from the backend:

| What to Validate in UI | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Notice’s Last Processing Stage | The Portal checks the Last Processing Stage to confirm whether the Notice is at a stage that permits TS |
| Payment Status | The Portal checks the following fields to verify if the Notice has been paid: Suspension Type CRS Reason for Suspension |
| Permanent Suspensions (Non-Payment) | The Portal checks the following fields to verify if the Notice is permanently suspended: Suspension Type EPR Reason for Suspension If the Notice has a permanent suspension, the Portal then checks whether the Suspension Code permits a TS. |

**2.6.3 Validating TS Requests in the OCMS Backend**

- The OCMS Backend is the main processor for TS requests. 

- The TS function in the OCMS Backend can be triggered by the following sources:

| Source | Scenario |
| --- | --- |
| OCMS Backend | Auto trigger TS when the Notice Processing workflow encounter exceptions, for example: Record not found at LTA, MHA or DataHive Current Offender is listed in the HST list |
| OCMS Staff Portal | OICs manual TS one or more Notices for investigation |
| PLUS Staff Portal | Appeal Processing Officers (PLMs) manual TS one or more Notices for specific reasons, for example: Notice is linked to a new Appeal Suspension is extended for further investigation Reduction has been approved and the Notice is suspended during the payment grace period |
| PLUS Backend | PLUS Backend auto triggers TS-APP when an eAppeal has been submitted via the eService |

- When the OCMS Backend receives the request to perform TS, it will check and enforce:

| Rules | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Authentication of Source and Permission | Source has a valid token for the API call Source is allowed to trigger suspension for the given Suspension Code |
| Global Rules | Last Processing Stage is at a TS-permissible stage Notice is not paid or partially paid EPR Reason of Suspension for current PS allows additional TS Checks Suspended Notices database for overlapping active suspensions |
| Suspension Code Specific Rules | Requestor has permission to suspend with the specific Suspension Code Last Processing Stage is at a TS-permissible stage for the specific Suspension Code |

- The Backend validation serves as the final safeguard that ensures that the system’s suspension rules are enforced consistently and securely.

**Section 3: OCMS Staff Portal Manual TS**

**3.1 Use case**

- The manual TS function in the OCMS Staff Portal allows authorised OICs to temporarily suspend Notices.

- Users can search for the notices using the Staff Portal’s Search Notice function by:Entering search parameters to retrieve one or more Notices
- Uploading a spreadsheet containing a list of notice numbers to retrieve the Notices.

- From the search results, Users can apply TS using one of two ways: Select one or more Notices in the Search Result interface and trigger the TS operation from the drop-down list to initiate a batch TS
- Click on a Notice to view the details and apply the TS from the View Notice Details interface 

- When the TS is initiated from the Staff Portal, the Staff Portal validates the suspension eligibility of each Notice before redirecting Users to the Suspension Detail Page to: Select the TS Suspension Code 
- Review/edit the Suspension Period 
- Input Suspension Remarks, if any
- After the Suspension Details are submitted, OCMS sends the suspension details to the OCMS backend for processing. 
- If TS is successful, Users will be presented with a success message on screen; an error message will be displayed is the suspension is not successful.

**Section 4: Auto Temporary Suspensions in OCMS**

**4.1 Use case**

- The OCMS system will automatically trigger Temporary Suspensions to Notices when pre-defined scenarios occur.

- The scenarios are pre-defined in the Notice Processing Workflow at various Processing Stages.
- When the conditions of the scenarios are met OCMS will automatically Suspend the Notices with pre-defined Suspension Codes and alert OICs about the exceptions. 
**4.2 Scenarios that Auto Trigger TS**

| Scenario | Suspension Code | Auto Triggered by |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Exceptions occur when the OCMS workflow encounters data errors during UEN-related queries to DataHive, specifically: DataHive responds that Company is deregistered OCMS uses the ranking criteria to identify a director, owner, or partner from DataHive response. However, there's no suitable match for any of these roles in the DataHive response. (Post MVP) | ACR | OCMS Backend |
| Notice has been linked to an Appeal via the eService | APP | PLUS Backend |
| Notice for VIP vehicle remains unpaid at the end of the RR3/DR3 Processing Stage and needs to be suspended to prevent it from escalating to the Court stage | CLV | OCMS Backend |
| Offender is no longer residing at the registered address, and no new address has been furnished. | HST | OCMS Backend |
| Exceptions occur when OCMS Workflow encounter data exception for Offender particulars queries to MHA, specifically: MHA responds that the Offender’s address is invalid MHA’s Exception Report indicates that the Offender’s ID number is invalid Offender’s ID number was sent to MHA but the MHA return file did not contain any record for the Offender ID | NRO | OCMS Backend |
| The vehicle number for a paid notice on the Internet does not match the vehicle number for the corresponding notice in the Intranet. | PAM | OCMS Backend |
| Driver details furnished via the eService requires verification by the OIC. | PDP | OCMS Backend |
| Exceptions occur when the OCMS workflow encounters data errors during Vehicle Ownership queries to LTA, specifically: File error represented by LTA error codes A, B or C Vehicle record error represented by LTA error codes 2, 3 or 4 | ROV | OCMS Backend |
| When an interface failure or system issues are detected during Notice processing | SYS | OCMS Backend |

**Section 5: Temporary Suspension initiated by PLUS**

**5.1 Use case**

- PLUS can apply a TS via an API provided by OCMS.
- The PLUS system and PLUS Users will initiate TS under the following circumstances:One or more notices are linked to an appeal.
- Appeal Processing Officers (PLMs) suspend a notice while the appeal is under review.
- PLMs extend an existing suspension to allow more time for investigation.
- Call Centre Officers suspend a notice while checks are ongoing.
- PLMs reduce the Notice amount payable and grant the offender a payment grace period.
- When a suspension is initiated through the PLUS Staff Portal or backend, the PLUS system shall provide the suspension details, which will be logged in OCMS in the Suspended Notices database table.

- Upon receiving the request, OCMS validates the submitted suspension data before proceeding with the TS.

- PLUS can apply TS to multiple Notices simultaneously.

**5.2 Process Flow

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

**![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)**

**Flow 1: When a Notice is added to an Appeal **

| No. | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Start | The PLM starts the process in the PLUS Staff Portal. |
| 2 | PLM Wants to Add Notice(s) to an Appeal | The PLM wants to add one or more Notices to an Appeal. |
| 3 | User Search for Notice(s) | The PLM searches for the relevant Notice(s) to add to the Appeal |
| 4 | PLM Select Notice(s) to Add to Appeal | The user selects the desired Notice(s) to include in the Appeal. |
| 5 | PLM Add Notice(s) to the Appeal | The selected Notice(s) are added to the Appeal. |
| 6 | Trigger PLUS Backend to Apply TS-APP | When the PLM adds the Notice(s), the PLUS Staff Portal triggers the PLUS Backend to apply the TS-APP suspension. |
| 7 | PLUS Backend Calls OCMS Backend API | The PLUS Backend calls the OCMS Backend API to request for the TS-APP suspension. |
| 8 | OCMS Backend Checks if TS is Allowed | The OCMS backend validates whether the TS request is allowed under the system rules. If one or more Notice(s) is not eligible, the OCMS Staff Portal backend responds to the PLUS Backend with an error message. If the Notice(s) is eligible, the OCMS backend responds to the PLUS Backend with a success message. |
| 10 | PLUS Backend Responds to PLUS Staff Portal | The PLUS Backend then sends the result back to the PLUS Staff Portal. |
| 11 | PLUS Staff Portal Displays TS Result | The PLUS Staff Portal displays a message showing whether the TS was successfully applied or failed. |
| 12 | End | The process ends. |

**Flow 2: When PLM Manually Applies TS to a Notice that has been added to an Appeal **

| No. | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Start | The process begins when the PLM wishes to apply TS to a Notice that is linked to an Appeal. |
| 2 | PLM Wants to Apply TS to Notice(s) for Appeal | The PLM retrieves the Appeal case and selects the Notices to TS |
| 3 | Validate Eligibility | The PLUS Staff Portal checks if the selected Notice(s) are eligible for TS. If one or more Notice(s) is not eligible, the PLUS Staff Portal informs the PLM that TS cannot be applied to the Notice(s). If the Notice(s) is eligible, OCMS proceeds to Step 4. |
| 4 | Redirect to Suspension Detail Page | The PLUS Staff Portal redirects the PLM to the Suspension Detail Page so that the PLM can input the suspension details, such as: Select TS for the Suspension Type Select the Suspension Code Review the Suspension Duration Input Suspension Remarks (if any) |
| 5 | Input Suspension Details &amp; Submit | The PLM enters the Suspension details and submits the form. |
| 6 | Send TS Request to PLUS Backend | The PLUS Staff Portal sends the suspension request to the PLUS backend. |
| 7 | PLUS Backend Calls OCMS Backend API | The PLUS Backend calls the OCMS Backend API to request for suspension. |
| 8 | OCMS Backend Checks if TS is Allowed | The OCMS backend validates whether the TS request is allowed under the system rules. If one or more Notice(s) is not eligible, the OCMS Staff Portal backend responds to the PLUS Backend with an error message. If the Notice(s) is eligible, the OCMS backend responds to the PLUS Backend with a success message. |
| 9 | PLUS Backend Responds to PLUS Staff Portal | The PLUS Backend then sends the result back to the PLUS Staff Portal. |
| 10 | PLUS Staff Portal Displays TS Result | The PLUS Staff Portal displays a message showing whether the TS was successfully applied or failed. |
| 11 | End | The process ends. |

**5.3 Suspension Codes used by PLUS

5.3.1 Suspension Code**

| Suspension Code | Suspension Code | Reason of Suspension |
| --- | --- | --- |
| TS | APE | Notice suspension extended as Appeal Processing Officer conducts further investigation. |
| TS | APP | Notice suspended as an Appeal has been created for this notice and the Appeal is being reviewed by Appeal Processing Officers. |
| TS | CCE | Call Centre Agent is responding to an enquiry for the Notice. |
| TS | RED | Appeal Processing Officer has approved a fee reduction with a fixed payment grace period after reviewing the Appeal. |
| TS | MS | Suspension code is used for all other scenarios which have no specific reasons. |
| TS | PRI | Appeal Processing Officer or OCMS OIC have verified that the Offender is currently in prison. |

**Section 6: Looping Temporary Suspensions**

**6.1 Use case**

- Looping TS is applicable only to selected Suspension Codes, specifically:CLV
- HST
- Looping occurs when a Notice's TS period expires and the suspension is re-applied immediately.
- A Looping TS will continue to re-apply the same suspension until it is lifted manually by an OIC. 
*Note: While it is called a Looping TS, the function to detect the Suspension Code and auto re-apply the TS is triggered by the Suspension Revival function. *

**6.2 Process Flow 

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)**

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended. 

**![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)**

- The Looping TS function is part of the Revival Cron. The Flow above illustrates the Revival Cron flow and the Looping TS processes are marked in red. 

- The table below only focuses on Apply Looping TS function. It will not describe the Suspension Revival function which is covered in the OCMS 19 Functional Document.

| No. | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Start | The process begins when the daily OCMS Backend cron job runs to check for suspended notices due for revival. |
| 2 | Query Suspended Notices DB | OCMS queries the Suspended Notice DB table for any TS records that are due for revival today. If no record is returned, OCMS ends the revival process. If records are returned, OCMS will proceed to the check the lifted suspension’s code is Looping TS. |
| 3 | Check Suspension Code | The system checks if the lifted suspension’s code is CLV or HST to determine if Looping TS should apply. If the Suspension Code is CLV or HST, OCMS proceeds to Step 4 to revive the existing suspension code and re-apply the suspension. If the Suspension Code is neither CLV nor HST, OCMS continues to process the Notice along the OCMS 19 revival workflow (white boxes in flow). |
| 4 | Lift Suspension | For each matching record, the system lifts the suspension and updates the Suspended Notices database accordingly. |
| 5 | Initiate Looping TS | If the suspension code is CLV or HST, the system starts the Looping TS process for that notice. |
| 6 | Calculate Revival Date | The OCMS backend calculates a new Due Date for Revival for the new TS record. |
| 7 | Create New TS Record | OCMS then creates a new record in the Suspended Notices DB table with the new TS details. |
| 8 | Update VON | OCMS then updates the Valid Offence Notice DB to reflect the new TS suspension information. |
| 9 | End | The new TS is now active and will be checked again by the cron job on its due revival date, continuing the loop as needed. |
